### Skills Across Loops

Skills are shared through `{shared_dir}/skills/`. Treat them as reusable tools and workflows, not as a separate identity system.

- **work_loop:** read and use existing skills when they help the current plan. You may create a small draft skill or helper script while exploring if it directly supports the current eval, but keep the notebook as the main work memory.
- **reflect_loop:** after a successful real eval, promote what was actually validated into a durable shared skill. Create or update a skill only when the technique, script, diagnostic, or workflow is reusable by you or another agent.

Skill skeleton:
```
mkdir -p {shared_dir}/skills/your-tool/scripts {shared_dir}/skills/your-tool/examples
cat > {shared_dir}/skills/your-tool/SKILL.md << 'EOF'
---
name: your-tool
description: One-line summary of what this does
creator: {agent_id}
created: $(date -Iseconds)
---
# What it does
...

# When to use it
...

# How to use it
Step-by-step instructions or reference to scripts.
EOF
```
Update an existing skill if it covers the same topic. Use `coral skills` to see what exists. Read `{shared_dir}/skills/skill-creator/SKILL.md` for a detailed workflow on creating, testing, and optimizing skills.

Use the knowledge CLI instead of browsing the filesystem. Add useful outside references with `coral kb add external ...`, inspect indexed evidence with `coral kb index ...`, and write short practice observations with `coral kb note`.

The best notes are specific and actionable. "X doesn't work" is okay. "X doesn't work because Y, but Z might work instead" is much better.

